english:
  title: Proclamation
  author: Choe Eung-cheong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Hear this decree. The Buddha's law knows no boundary between center and periphery. The luminous master emerged from the land of Shen-dan, and as heaven opened in primordial chaos, sacred teachings were revealed to the sage-kings. The banner of the Buddha's dharma was planted in the torrents of the world, and the nation's destiny opened unto eternity. Such towering merit deserves our luminous praise.

    The Dharma-master, whose name is thus recorded, possessed from birth a great aspiration, and the world called him a worthy vessel of the teaching. He sought the subtle source in the ocean of nature without lingering in emptiness, and gained the true seal in the forest of meditation, himself penetrating profound truth. Having exhausted the depths of the Buddha and his ancestors, he became moreover versed in the remaining arts of yin and yang. As his secret teachings prepared for transmission, suddenly a stranger arrived in audience. With unobstructed supernatural powers, he gazed upon the great earth and overlooked nothing. Knowing that the period of change and renewal had come, he perceived that one bearing the mandate of heaven would surely arise. Thus he pointed to his ancestor's dwelling place, saying, "A sage shall be born here," and sealed one volume of scripture to present in advance to the unborn superior man, that when his time of awakening came, it would show him the foundation laid in ages past. Heaven lent its hand to this work of uncommon grace.

    When our imperial predecessor honored him further with the greatest of titles, how could I, in my humble person, fail to honor my royal father's will? Let us perform the solemn rituals of this age and bestow the eternal radiance of a thousand generations. Alas! Our nation has its illuminated master, the Buddha has his true heir. His name shines with the sun and moon, his virtue flows with heaven and earth. Who can fathom its beginning? Who can know its utmost reach? We hereby command the proper ministry to prepare the ceremonies of enshrinement and elevation, appointing him National Preceptor of First Awakening. Let the responsible authorities carry this into effect.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Shen-dan (震旦): Classical Chinese name for China, suggesting the transmission of Buddhism from India through China to Korea'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Six supernatural powers (六通): Buddhist concept of divine abilities gained through meditation'
  - key: ''
    value: 'National Preceptor of First Awakening (先覺國師): A high honorific title conferring both spiritual and political authority'
